### Automatically Generate a Table of Contents in LaTeX

To automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX, you can use the following commands:

1. **\tableofcontents**: This command generates the table of contents based on the sections and subsections in your document.

2. **\addcontentsline**: This command adds an entry to the table of contents for a specific section or subsection.

Here's an example of how to use these commands:

```bash
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.

\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command generates a table of contents at the beginning of the document. The `\addcontentsline` command is used to add entries for each section and subsection.

Note that the `\addcontentsline` command takes three arguments: the name of the file where the table of contents is stored (usually `toc`), the level of the entry (usually `section` or `subsection`), and the text to be displayed in the table of contents.

By default, LaTeX automatically generates a table of contents based on the sections and subsections in your document. However, you can customize the appearance of the table of contents by using additional commands and packages.

